		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The research planned is in connection with a path decomposition involving the excursions of a process above and below a fixed level.  This decomposition is known to hold for various types of Markov processes, eg random walks, Levy processes and diffusions and has found many applications.  Recently Chaumont has shown that this decomposition gives a very natural way to establish the Wendel-Port-Dassios identity for several types of processes (including some  which are not Markov).  Also Doney and Yor have given an in-depth analysis of `doubly perturbed Brownian motion' (a variant of Brownian motion which is also non-Markovian), leaning heavily on this same decomposition.  The main objectives of this programme are to establish this decomposition for as large a class of processes as possible, and to determine whether certain relationships between the original process and the new processes, which are important for applications, continue to hold.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
